{"title_page": "Jefferson Coates", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name                = Jefferson Coates\n|birth_date          = {{Birth date|1843|8|24}}\n|death_date          = {{Death date and age|1880|1|27|1843|8|24}}\n|birth_place         = [[Grant County, Wisconsin]]\n|death_place         = \n|placeofburial       = Dorchester Cemetery [[Dorchester, Nebraska]]\n|placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n|image               = Jefferson Coates (1843-1880).jpg\n|caption             = \n|nickname            = \n|allegiance          = {{flag|United States of America|1861}}<br/>[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch              = {{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears        = 1861 - 1864\n|rank                = [[File:Union army cpt rank insignia.jpg|35px]] [[Brevet (military)|Brevet]] [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|commands            = \n|unit                = {{Flagicon|Wisconsin}} [[7th Wisconsin Volunteer Infantry Regiment|7th Regiment, Wisconsin Volunteer Infantry ]] - Company H \n|battles             = [[American Civil War]]<br/>*[[Battle of South Mountain]]<br/>*[[Battle of Gettysburg]]\n|awards              = {{flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n|laterwork           = \n}}\n'''Francis Jefferson Coates''' (August 24, 1843 &ndash; January 27, 1880) was a soldier in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]] and one of 64 men who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for actions during the [[Battle of Gettysburg]].\n\n==Biography==\nCoates was born 24 August 1843 in [[Grant County, Wisconsin]]<ref name=\"Land\">{{cite news|title=Land Donated to Blind School|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10173062/jefferson_coates_18431880/|newspaper=The Daily Standard|date=June 30, 1966|page=9|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 10, 2017 }} {{Open access}}</ref> to William Coates and Cynthia Cain. Although born in Grant County his official residence was listed as [[Boscobel, Wisconsin]].<ref>[https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/1661 Hall of Valor]</ref>\n\nCoates joined the [[Union Army]] on 29 August 1861 (a few days after his 18th birthday), and served with the 7th Wisconsin Infantry. He was wounded while fighting in the [[Battle of South Mountain]] and during the [[Battle of Gettysburg]] where he received the [[Medal of Honor]] and a brevet promotion to [[Captain (United States)|Captain]] for courage in battle.  During the Battle of Gettysburg he was shot in the face, causing him to lose both of his eyes.<ref name=\"Land\"/> He was mustered out for disability on September 1, 1864 at the end of his term of service.\n\nDespite having become completely blind, Coates learned how to make brooms after the war and married Rachael Sarah Drew April 21, 1867. Together they had five children and sometime between 1870 and 1873, they moved to [[Dorchester, Nebraska]].\n\nHe died of pneumonia in Dorchester, Nebraska January 27, 1880<ref name=\"Land\"/> and is buried in Dorchester Cemetery in Dorchester.\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Jefferson Coates County Campus for the Missouri School for the Blind was named after Coates.<ref name=\"Land\"/>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n<blockquote>For extraordinary heroism on 1 July 1863, while serving with Company H, 7th Wisconsin Infantry, in action at Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, for unsurpassed courage in battle, where he had both eyes shot out.</blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Battle of Gettysburg]]\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|19733|work=Claim to Fame: Medal of Honor recipients|accessdate=2009-08-16}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/moh/citations_1862_cwa/coates.html |title=Home of Heroes}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/whi/fullRecord.asp?id=3898&qstring=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wisconsinhistory.org%2Fwhi%2Fresults.asp%3Fsubject_narrow%3DVeterans |title=Wisconsin History}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/gravesites/states/pages_af/coates_jefferson.html |title=Home of Heroes grave}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=April 25, 2013 |url=http://civilwarintheeast.com/People/C/CoatesF.php |title=Civil War in the East}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coates, Jefferson}}\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1880 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Saline County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:People from Boscobel, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:People of Wisconsin in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Blind people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name                = Jefferson Coates\n|birth_date          = {{Birth date|1843|8|24}}\n|death_date          = {{Death date and age|1880|1|27|1843|8|24}}\n|birth_place         = [[Grant County, Wisconsin]]\n|death_place         = \n|placeofburial       = Dorchester Cemetery [[Dorchester, Nebraska]]\n|placeofburial_label = Place of burial\n|image               = Jefferson Coates (1843-1880).jpg\n|caption             = \n|nickname            = \n|allegiance          = {{flag|United States of America|1861}}<br/>[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch              = {{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears        = 1861 - 1864\n|rank                = [[File:Union army cpt rank insignia.jpg|35px]] [[Brevet (military)|Brevet]] [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|commands            = \n|unit                = {{Flagicon|Wisconsin}} Company H, [[7th Wisconsin Volunteer Infantry Regiment|7th Wisconsin Volunteer Infantry]]\n|battles             = [[American Civil War]]<br/>*[[Battle of South Mountain]]<br/>*[[Battle of Gettysburg]]\n|awards              = {{flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n|laterwork           = \n}}\n'''Francis Jefferson Coates''' (August 24, 1843 &ndash; January 27, 1880) was a soldier in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]] and one of 64 men who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for actions during the [[Battle of Gettysburg]].\n\n==Biography==\nCoates was born 24 August 1843 in [[Grant County, Wisconsin]]<ref name=\"Land\">{{cite news|title=Land Donated to Blind School|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10173062/jefferson_coates_18431880/|newspaper=The Daily Standard|date=June 30, 1966|page=9|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 10, 2017 }} {{Open access}}</ref> to William Coates and Cynthia Cain. Although born in Grant County his official residence was listed as [[Boscobel, Wisconsin]].<ref>[https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/1661 Hall of Valor]</ref>\n\nCoates joined the [[Union Army]] on 29 August 1861 (a few days after his 18th birthday), and served with the 7th Wisconsin Infantry. He was wounded while fighting in the [[Battle of South Mountain]] and during the [[Battle of Gettysburg]] where he received the [[Medal of Honor]] and a brevet promotion to [[Captain (United States)|Captain]] for courage in battle.  During the Battle of Gettysburg he was shot in the face, causing him to lose both of his eyes.<ref name=\"Land\"/> He was mustered out for disability on September 1, 1864 at the end of his term of service.\n\nDespite having become completely blind, Coates learned how to make brooms after the war and married Rachael Sarah Drew April 21, 1867. Together they had five children and sometime between 1870 and 1873, they moved to [[Dorchester, Nebraska]].\n\nHe died of pneumonia in Dorchester, Nebraska January 27, 1880<ref name=\"Land\"/> and is buried in Dorchester Cemetery in Dorchester.\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Jefferson Coates County Campus for the Missouri School for the Blind was named after Coates.<ref name=\"Land\"/>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n<blockquote>For extraordinary heroism on 1 July 1863, while serving with Company H, 7th Wisconsin Infantry, in action at Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, for unsurpassed courage in battle, where he had both eyes shot out.</blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Battle of Gettysburg]]\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|19733|work=Claim to Fame: Medal of Honor recipients|accessdate=2009-08-16}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/moh/citations_1862_cwa/coates.html |title=Home of Heroes}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/whi/fullRecord.asp?id=3898&qstring=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wisconsinhistory.org%2Fwhi%2Fresults.asp%3Fsubject_narrow%3DVeterans |title=Wisconsin History}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=September 29, 2010 |url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/gravesites/states/pages_af/coates_jefferson.html |title=Home of Heroes grave}}\n*{{Cite web |accessdate=April 25, 2013 |url=http://civilwarintheeast.com/People/C/CoatesF.php |title=Civil War in the East}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coates, Jefferson}}\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1880 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Saline County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:People from Boscobel, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:People of Wisconsin in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Blind people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jefferson_Coates"}
